High-confidence clusters

Airbnb listings are algorithmically clustered based on host, license and semi-anonymous geographic data. Each cluster should correspond to a building with multiple STR units (within a given range of accuracy).

[+] Learn more...

Dbscan clustering algorithms are applied over multiple phases to acquire final best-guess locations for suspected high-occupancy STR buildings. First listings are split into unique host-license groups, because hosts often use the same license number for all the units in a building. In phase I, the clustering algorithm overestimates cluster granularity, generating many small groups.

In the second phase of clustering, dbscan combines nearby sub-groups owned by the same host or corporation group, accounting for cases where one host uses multiple license numbers within the same building. The goal is identify groups of listings that likely belong to one building.

In buildings with many assumed listings, we can then exploit the semi-anonymized public location data to approximate a guess for the actual building location by taking the mean weighted coordinates of all the listings in a cluster. This strategy often leads directly to or near a building with confirmed STR units inside.

A repository containing the complete analysis stack is available on GitHub:
